and you will see more studios doing it.

665
00:44:41,165 --> 00:44:44,446
I think it is another beast for a AAA studio

666
00:44:44,946 --> 00:44:47,567
to tackle a four-day week than it is an indie studio.

667
00:44:48,487 --> 00:44:50,208
Just the sheer scale and coordination

668
00:44:50,868 --> 00:44:53,049
of like a 400-person team working on a game.

669
00:44:53,189 --> 00:44:54,269
I don't know how that would work.

670
00:44:55,249 --> 00:44:58,130
But I think for indies, I expect that it's going to be

671
00:44:58,190 --> 00:45:00,351
like more and more regular to see studios

672
00:45:00,391 --> 00:45:01,171
on the four-day work week.

673
00:45:02,701 --> 00:45:24,153
Yeah, to speak back to something that Chris mentioned, in terms of, you know, hiring people and attracting talent. That is one of the main things that small studios can offer. I can't imagine that this won't become the norm in the future. And I think it should become the norm. I don't see any reason for it not to be.

674
00:45:24,653 --> 00:45:29,614
And part of that is retaining talent, attracting talent, because, you know, as small companies,

675
00:45:29,694 --> 00:45:34,136
we don't compete with the big studios in terms of salary or benefits or whatever.

676
00:45:35,016 --> 00:45:39,437
So we have to find other ways to engage people in meaningful ways and make our

677
00:45:39,677 --> 00:45:47,759
work environments attractive for them. Honestly, maybe this is the pandemic,

678
00:45:47,979 --> 00:45:50,820
like existentialism speaking a little bit.

679
00:45:51,402 --> 00:45:54,644
But I think that if there was a will,

680
00:45:55,825 --> 00:45:58,887
any industry out there could go to 40 hours a week.

681
00:45:58,947 --> 00:46:02,549
It's just, it's more a matter of everyone wanting to do it.

682
00:46:03,149 --> 00:46:06,571
Like I think if all of the employees of Ubisoft

683
00:46:06,631 --> 00:46:08,512
woke up tomorrow and said,

684
00:46:08,592 --> 00:46:10,233
we only want to work four days or we quit.

685
00:46:11,115 --> 00:46:13,617
Like suddenly it would be, they figure it out, right?

686
00:46:13,818 --> 00:46:16,640
And that's like the magic of unions and co-ops

687
00:46:16,780 --> 00:46:19,302
and all these other like worker forces.

688
00:46:20,243 --> 00:46:21,384
It would be very, very difficult.

689
00:46:21,404 --> 00:46:22,265
I'm not saying it's easy.

690
00:46:22,305 --> 00:46:25,227
I'm not saying, I know that it would be even,

691
00:46:25,247 --> 00:46:27,409
you know, exponentially harder,

692
00:46:27,469 --> 00:46:29,030
the larger your organization is.

693
00:46:29,831 --> 00:46:33,234
Hats off to Chris already for 30 people versus 11,

694
00:46:35,255 --> 00:46:37,377
but I absolutely think it'll become more and more normal.

695
00:46:37,497 --> 00:46:38,318
And I hope it does.

696
00:46:38,358 --> 00:46:38,758
And I hope.

697
00:46:39,475 --> 00:46:45,718
the most for our most vulnerable workers for like QA and community management and all the

698
00:46:45,739 --> 00:46:51,062
people that are exploited more that they get to have more and more the kind of lifestyle that

699
00:46:51,082 --> 00:46:58,326
they want for their talents. Sorry, Salim, you were going to say something in the middle of the

700
00:46:58,346 --> 00:47:03,269
night. I kept talking. No, no, no. I forgot what I was going to say. Sorry.

701
00:47:04,412 --> 00:47:06,934
Cool, so let's just wrap up and then we can go to Q&A.

702
00:47:06,954 --> 00:47:08,776
But the last question I wanted to ask the group,

703
00:47:09,957 --> 00:47:13,080
if there was just one thing that you'd recommend

704
00:47:13,121 --> 00:47:15,243
to any team considering a four-day work week,

705
00:47:15,263 --> 00:47:16,344
whether it's a piece of advice,

706
00:47:16,964 --> 00:47:18,546
a thing that you keep thinking about,

707
00:47:18,606 --> 00:47:21,689
what's that one thing that you would give to that group

708
00:47:21,809 --> 00:47:24,071
who is thinking about that four-day work week shift?

709
00:47:25,602 --> 00:47:34,350
Every single time that I run a postmortem in life, the one issue that keeps coming back in again and again is communication.

710
00:47:35,231 --> 00:47:44,140
There's always issues with communication in some form. And so I think that's one thing that you really, really need to work on. So, you know, optimizing meetings and making sure the

711
00:47:45,301 --> 00:47:55,551
There's a flow of communications from when things get decided to whoever needs to know those things, and not necessarily monopolizing everyone's time for meetings is something that's really important.

712
00:47:56,752 --> 00:48:02,277
Also, you know, going into a meeting with a schedule instead of just with already talking points that are pre planned.

713
00:48:02,935 --> 00:48:04,237
instead of kind of just winging it.

714
00:48:04,838 --> 00:48:05,519
That's a big one.

715
00:48:05,819 --> 00:48:09,644
Which was what we used to do, I think is really, really important because in the

716
00:48:09,724 --> 00:48:14,790
end you, you realize that on a five day week, you were, you were kind of already

717
00:48:14,870 --> 00:48:18,314
cheating on a lot of stuff, like, you know, cheating hours here and there with, you

718
00:48:18,334 --> 00:48:18,455
know,

719
00:48:19,646 --> 00:48:30,674
I'm going to attend this meeting, even though I have nothing to do with it, just because I wanted to see or understand what's going on, knowing that it was kind of going to be like a more relaxed hour where you might not need to have a brain as focused as you usually do.

720
00:48:31,394 --> 00:48:39,180
So that's the kind of stuff that I think really needs to get worked on the asynchronous communication also like as Tanya mentioned, it can be an issue of.

721
00:48:39,680 --> 00:48:44,042
someone's not there on a certain day or all that stuff are the things that we need to figure out.

722
00:48:44,583 --> 00:48:48,204
But if you if you do put the time in that and you can fix that part of it,

723
00:48:48,545 --> 00:48:53,207
the rest comes a lot much more naturally and easier than you might think to implement.

724
00:48:58,669 --> 00:48:59,290
Salim, Tanya.

725
00:49:01,888 --> 00:49:04,990
Yeah, I would say if you're a team considering the four day work week,

726
00:49:05,010 --> 00:49:08,453
the most important thing I would suggest to you is to consider unionizing.

727
00:49:09,314 --> 00:49:11,416
If you're a group of team members, you should

728
00:49:13,157 --> 00:49:16,080
build collective power because you can't trust people like us

729
00:49:16,120 --> 00:49:18,702
who are giving this talk right now as business owners.

730
00:49:20,123 --> 00:49:23,406
You know, we might be nice bosses, we might be good people,

731
00:49:24,086 --> 00:49:27,549
but there's nothing stopping us from reverting that or changing things

732
00:49:27,609 --> 00:49:29,531
or exploiting in other ways. And so.

733
00:49:30,372 --> 00:49:32,453
The four day workweek is a great place

734
00:49:32,493 --> 00:49:34,593
to actually start organizing your workplace

735
00:49:34,633 --> 00:49:39,335
because it's a really easy place to unify a lot of things

736
00:49:39,355 --> 00:49:40,975
where you can be like, yeah, I would love that.

737
00:49:41,075 --> 00:49:42,115
And my team would love that.

738
00:49:42,135 --> 00:49:44,576
And that's a place where you find common ground

739
00:49:44,616 --> 00:49:46,057
to building solidarity.

740
00:49:46,077 --> 00:49:48,197
So I really recommend reaching out to organizations

741
00:49:48,217 --> 00:49:50,938
like Game Workers Unite and other union organizations

742
00:49:51,018 --> 00:49:54,159
on how to unionize, because then you can take some

743
00:49:54,179 --> 00:49:58,280
of that power into the team's hand and enforce and ensure

744
00:49:59,758 --> 00:50:05,585
proper boundaries and good work life balance in a way that you can't by just trusting the owners of a studio.

745
00:50:07,882 --> 00:50:15,926
Well put. My number one advice to both the bosses who are listening and the workers is to set a goal for yourself.

746
00:50:17,246 --> 00:50:27,230
If you're a boss, like know what your goals are. Like for us, if our goals were mental health, that's something we can look at and measure whether or not we should continue and it was successful for us so we continued.

747
00:50:27,310 --> 00:50:33,813
But if, and as a worker, like what are your goals for those Fridays? Are you going to use them to relax? Are you going to use them to have a side project?

748
00:50:33,913 --> 00:50:34,413
Like I think.

749
00:50:35,809 --> 00:50:36,930
everybody feels better about it

750
00:50:36,970 --> 00:50:39,912
when they know what their goals are for a change like this

751
00:50:40,412 --> 00:50:43,954
and see the results through that lens

752
00:50:44,054 --> 00:50:46,495
rather than after six weeks,

753
00:50:47,236 --> 00:50:49,477
trying to look back and remember how it felt before.

754
00:50:52,159 --> 00:50:54,220
Awesome, well, thank you all on the panel.

755
00:50:54,740 --> 00:50:58,662
I think we have about nine minutes for Q&A.

756
00:50:58,902 --> 00:51:01,244
Is there anyone who wants to ask any questions

757
00:51:01,284 --> 00:51:01,724
for our panel?

