00:51:09,344 --> 00:51:12,726
Kit Fox might be hiring a programmer in the coming year

759
00:51:12,846 --> 00:51:16,207
or so, if anyone wants to ask about that.

760
00:51:16,227 --> 00:51:19,069
I don't have any details yet, but keep an eye

761
00:51:19,209 --> 00:51:21,950
on our Twitter and website.

762
00:51:23,511 --> 00:51:25,191
It is hard to hire programmers, I hear.

763
00:51:25,332 --> 00:51:29,834
So I'm hoping this will be a benefit.

764
00:51:30,894 --> 00:51:30,954
OK.

765
00:51:33,994 --> 00:51:35,974
You hear me, I think.

766
00:51:36,275 --> 00:51:38,716
I have actually a few questions.

767
00:51:38,756 --> 00:51:40,556
First of all, it's about the leading people

768
00:51:41,657 --> 00:51:43,638
because there are usually people

769
00:51:43,658 --> 00:51:45,639
who are very focused and efficient,

770
00:51:46,359 --> 00:51:48,860
and at the same time you work with people

771
00:51:48,880 --> 00:51:50,200
who are not very efficient

772
00:51:50,300 --> 00:51:52,681
and have some problems with time organization.

773
00:51:53,322 --> 00:51:54,722
And how do you deal with that?

774
00:51:54,962 --> 00:51:55,763
Where are the traps?

775
00:51:56,903 --> 00:51:58,324
How do we deal with both attitudes?

776
00:51:58,404 --> 00:52:01,625
And how did the people switch to the four days a week?

777
00:52:04,708 --> 00:52:07,970
I mean, I can say for us, I mean, that has always been the case, right?

778
00:52:08,010 --> 00:52:12,093
Like on a five day week, there are some people who flail with their time

779
00:52:12,113 --> 00:52:13,794
and organization and other people who.

780
00:52:15,011 --> 00:52:16,112
who are very good at it.

781
00:52:16,452 --> 00:52:18,774
And it's always a question of working with each person.

782
00:52:18,974 --> 00:52:21,156
Like I'm not gonna have the same system

783
00:52:21,176 --> 00:52:22,116
that works for everybody.

784
00:52:22,196 --> 00:52:23,437
Some people I gotta remind them

785
00:52:23,457 --> 00:52:24,798
of other timesheets every two days.

786
00:52:25,499 --> 00:52:27,520
And other people, I leave them alone for two weeks

787
00:52:27,560 --> 00:52:30,263
and they come back with more spreadsheets

788
00:52:30,283 --> 00:52:31,083
than I could have imagined.

789
00:52:32,204 --> 00:52:33,965
And this does make it more evident,

790
00:52:34,125 --> 00:52:36,787
but I think if you're worried about someone

791
00:52:37,068 --> 00:52:38,409
not working hard enough,

792
00:52:38,529 --> 00:52:40,190
like that's a separate conversation

793
00:52:40,270 --> 00:52:42,131
from how many hours you expect them to work.

794
00:52:43,034 --> 00:52:48,677
Yeah, something to add to that is you can always help enable people to be better with those things,

795
00:52:49,117 --> 00:52:54,639
but also production needs to also be flexible enough to not treat every person as one size fits all.

796
00:52:54,999 --> 00:53:00,062
And sometimes production actually has to just measure that different people have different outputs and you plan around that.

797
00:53:00,802 --> 00:53:06,264
So yes, you give them support, you help them have the tools to improve where you think it's necessary,

798
00:53:06,545 --> 00:53:07,785
but also production.

799
00:53:09,122 --> 00:53:10,703
You can't just have like an artist and be like,

800
00:53:10,723 --> 00:53:13,484
well, I need you to make, you know, 15 assets a week.

801
00:53:13,584 --> 00:53:15,886
And if the artist can only make seven assets a week,

802
00:53:16,126 --> 00:53:16,866
that's their pace.

803
00:53:16,926 --> 00:53:18,347
You have to plan around that.

804
00:53:18,567 --> 00:53:21,509
You know, I think it's very important to not treat people

805
00:53:21,669 --> 00:53:26,631
as a, to just really not treat folks

806
00:53:26,651 --> 00:53:27,972
with a one size fits all approach.

807
00:53:29,373 --> 00:53:31,954
Yeah, and always giving feedback is also something

808
00:53:31,974 --> 00:53:33,775
that I think is super important

809
00:53:33,975 --> 00:53:35,836
and having that open conversation.

810
00:53:36,591 --> 00:53:40,733
when you feel like someone might be underperforming or stuff like that are just like general things

811
00:53:40,773 --> 00:53:45,655
but again that are those are issues that are as real on a five-day week than they are on a four-day week.

812
00:53:47,616 --> 00:53:54,439
Okay another question is about scaling it because you work in these studios do you think or do you

813
00:53:54,500 --> 00:54:00,562
feel that it can be scaled to bigger studios what are the possible traps there and do you have

814
00:54:00,622 --> 00:54:01,363
anything to recommend?

815
00:54:04,751 --> 00:54:08,312
I guess I would recommend trialing it

816
00:54:08,432 --> 00:54:10,092
in the most isolated department.

817
00:54:10,172 --> 00:54:12,993
I worked at a large studio many years ago,

818
00:54:13,093 --> 00:54:14,133
so it's been a while,

819
00:54:15,213 --> 00:54:17,873
but I imagine the more tightly integrated

820
00:54:17,973 --> 00:54:21,434
and the more cross collaborative they are,

821
00:54:21,494 --> 00:54:25,355
the harder that department will be to trial a four-day week

822
00:54:26,895 --> 00:54:28,035
and doing it across the studio

823
00:54:28,055 --> 00:54:30,876
would probably be a complete problem.

824
00:54:33,058 --> 00:54:40,721
So yeah, maybe there's a particularly segregated group that can do a milestone on 40 weeks

825
00:54:41,341 --> 00:54:42,361
and then compare notes.

826
00:54:43,162 --> 00:54:44,322
What is the trial period?

827
00:54:45,863 --> 00:54:50,165
For us, we started with six weeks and then we moved it to three months.

828
00:54:50,725 --> 00:54:53,346
So we doubled it after six weeks were successful.

829
00:54:55,667 --> 00:55:00,889
But I guess it would depend on the kind of milestones that that project has.

830
00:55:01,851 --> 00:55:03,734
I'd be happy to talk with somebody in more depth.

831
00:55:03,774 --> 00:55:07,560
If you want to email me or tweet at me, we can organize a chat.

832
00:55:08,141 --> 00:55:08,902
I can give some advice.

833
00:55:10,389 --> 00:55:14,331
I've never worked in a AAA studio, so I'm not really equipped to answer that question.

834
00:55:14,932 --> 00:55:20,876
I know that in Montreal, Eidos Square Enix is looking at trying the four-day week or they're

835
00:55:20,916 --> 00:55:26,840
implementing it in some form. So, you know, I would maybe reach out to them and see how they do it, but

836
00:55:28,060 --> 00:55:32,463
I'm just, I don't have enough knowledge of the AAA space to be able to add anything.

837
00:55:34,730 --> 00:55:39,873
Okay, and last question, I would like to ask about Agile. Do you work in Agile system? If so,

838
00:55:41,334 --> 00:55:45,396
please elaborate on, did you squeeze all these meetings? This is pretty expensive,

839
00:55:45,416 --> 00:55:50,319
you have planning, refinement, then you have to summarize all this up. And four-day weeks

840
00:55:50,399 --> 00:55:55,502
seems to be pretty short to do all these things. How long your sprint lasts?

