00:56:00,405 --> 00:56:00,985
This is the last one.

843
00:56:01,085 --> 00:56:03,406
So if you could keep the answer brief.

844
00:56:05,422 --> 00:56:05,803
Yeah.

845
00:56:05,843 --> 00:56:07,407
We can run over a little bit.

846
00:56:08,208 --> 00:56:10,092
And hopefully, you were here at the beginning

847
00:56:10,133 --> 00:56:11,395
to get their contact info.

848
00:56:11,435 --> 00:56:13,099
And if not, we'll put it up at the end.

849
00:56:14,121 --> 00:56:16,025
Can I take this one real quick?

850
00:56:16,668 --> 00:56:21,169
I don't think Agile is designed for video games. I think you have to take Agile and make it work

851
00:56:21,249 --> 00:56:25,730
for video games. There are elements of Agile that you take and implement but you cannot get away

852
00:56:25,770 --> 00:56:31,051
from waterfall elements as well. I think you design the systems for your particular games

853
00:56:31,111 --> 00:56:37,393
and teams. You don't just adhere to Agile blindly or religiously and that's how you make it work

854
00:56:37,413 --> 00:56:39,093
with the times and the constraints that you have.

855
00:56:39,697 --> 00:56:41,358
For what it's worth, we do two week sprints.

856
00:56:41,678 --> 00:56:44,020
And yeah, Selim is correct, it's customized.

857
00:56:44,080 --> 00:56:47,643
But we do cross department show off

858
00:56:47,884 --> 00:56:49,925
and then sprint review and then sprint planning

859
00:56:50,026 --> 00:56:52,067
on Wednesday mornings, every two weeks.

860
00:56:52,388 --> 00:56:54,409
And the total is about two hours.

861
00:56:54,770 --> 00:56:57,332
It's very unusual that it lasts more than two hours total.

