00:57:05,560 --> 00:57:07,842
I wanted to come back to a point I think Salim, you mentioned.

865
00:57:09,383 --> 00:57:14,067
You had to hire another person for your community manager because they were, you know,

866
00:57:14,528 --> 00:57:15,949
there was so much focus on that one person.

867
00:57:16,309 --> 00:57:19,572
How do you have that conversation with that person without making them to feel

868
00:57:20,312 --> 00:57:25,119
Like they're not doing enough or like that you're trying to replace them because I can

869
00:57:25,159 --> 00:57:27,321
see how that can easily feel like you're being replaced.

870
00:57:27,341 --> 00:57:30,245
Like, oh, we're hiring another person just to help you with your work.

871
00:57:30,305 --> 00:57:31,206
Don't worry about it.

872
00:57:31,266 --> 00:57:33,789
So how do you have that conversation that is meaningful?

873
00:57:34,853 --> 00:57:40,618
Yeah, well, so at Co-op, the core full-time team members are co-owners of the studio.

874
00:57:40,738 --> 00:57:45,763
So there's a level of job security that that I think already kind of brings in.

875
00:57:46,723 --> 00:57:50,527
In our particular case, actually, our community manager was the person who was like,

876
00:57:50,687 --> 00:57:53,569
this is insane, this is not fair, and this is too much.

877
00:57:54,290 --> 00:57:57,492
And so that was a reaction to them bringing up their need for help.

878
00:57:58,093 --> 00:58:01,215
But in other situations where we've noticed people need additional support,

879
00:58:01,316 --> 00:58:03,958
it's kind of just like, hey, this is something we're noticing.

880
00:58:04,178 --> 00:58:10,123
we think you need support. And if that's a threat or a problem or a fear for them then it's just a matter of having a

881
00:58:10,163 --> 00:58:17,269
conversation being like let's lay it all down on the table and talk this out and just be mature about it. And I do think

882
00:58:17,329 --> 00:58:24,375
being a co-op helps in a lot of ways towards that feeling of that fear of being replaced.

883
00:58:26,474 --> 00:58:31,017
Yeah, I know for us, one of the things that we do

884
00:58:31,097 --> 00:58:33,738
as a publisher is we do internal QA for our games

885
00:58:33,878 --> 00:58:36,319
and we found that QA didn't kind of get the same kind

886
00:58:36,339 --> 00:58:40,502
of productivity boost that some of the other pieces

887
00:58:40,522 --> 00:58:41,782
of our publishing program did.

888
00:58:42,043 --> 00:58:44,324
And so it became a conversation that got surfaced

889
00:58:44,364 --> 00:58:47,586
by the QA team that like, hey, like we're falling short.

890
00:58:47,686 --> 00:58:49,687
We're not, you know, we're not falling short 20%

891
00:58:50,127 --> 00:58:51,828
but we are definitely falling short on QA.

892
00:58:53,667 --> 00:58:55,688
You need, your team needs to be trusted

893
00:58:55,729 --> 00:58:58,670
to bring those things up and be able to respond to it.

